

a.) I will be using Dynamic Programming as I will be relying on previous subsequent strings that are partially part of the word
we are finding occurences of

PSEUDOCODE

INPUT NUMBER OF TEST CASES
FOR EVERY TEST CASE:
    INPUT VALUES FOR x AND z
    output = COUNT(x, z)
    PRINT output

COUNT(x, z)
    m = LENGTH(x)
    n = LENGTH(z)
    
    CREATE dp TABLE WITH (m+1) ROWS AND (n+1) COLUMNS INITIALIZED TO 0
    
    FOR i FROM 0 TO m:
        dp[i][0] = 1
    
    FOR i FROM 1 TO m:
        FOR j FROM 1 TO n:
            IF x[i-1] EQUALS z[j-1] THEN:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j]
            ELSE:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j]
    
    RETURN dp[m][n]
d.)
Time Complexity
Case	Complexity	Explanation
Best Case	O(m × n)	The algorithm must fill every cell in the DP table regardless of input. Even if Z is empty (n=0), we still need O(m) time to set base cases.
Worst Case	O(m × n)	The nested loops always run (m × n) times. Character comparisons and additions are constant time operations.
Average Case	O(m × n)	No early termination possible. The entire table must be computed.
Where:

m = length of string X

n = length of string Z